The man accused of smashing the doors and windows of the Constitutional Court in Braamfontein has opted not to apply for bail. eNCA reporter Heidi Giokos has more on this story. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The man accused of smashing the doors and windows of the Constitutional Court in Braamfontein has opted not to apply for bail. Paul Makaula has appeared in the Hillbrow magistrate’s court. He is facing a charge of malicious damage to property. READ: Zondo concerned about ConCourt attack Makaula was out on parole when he decided to smash the glass doors and windows of the highest court in the land on Wednesday. He was convicted of murdering his girlfriend in 2010 and has been out on parole since 2019. The NPA's Phindi Mjonondwane said, “we can confirm that is accused is currently serving parole under correctional services, for a charge of murder. He was convicted in 2010 and parole in 2019. So now as the state we have the investigating officer will liaise correctional services whether or not the accused person contravened his parole.” READ: Suspect arrested for ConCourt attack expected in court The National Prosecuting Authority is forging ahead with its investigation. “Once the investigation process is concluded we will be in a better position to say whether or not it was politically motivated, or if it was just a criminal act, or whether or not its linked to the Cape Town one. Investigations are still ongoing. But at this point we have no information that the two are linked." Makaula has not opted for bail.